{
  "answer": "**Diwan-E-Zauq** by Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, chapter 56 (\"hungaama garm hasti-e-na-paaidaar ka\"). This ghazal's every couplet ends on the refrain \"is love\" (corresponding to radif: \"-aar ka\" in the original Urdu). It includes the specified couplets, plus the closing maqta with Zauq's signature warning about the tavern having no place for the wise.[^1][^2]\n\n**Chinar-on-the-grave couplet:**  \n\"My heart's own fire, in the grave, will glow, is love.  \nA tall Chinar upon my tomb will grow, is love.\"[^3]\n\n**Pomegranate-of-paradise couplet** (noting \"Eden's pomegranate\" renders \"baagh-e-khuld-e-bareen ke anaar,\" i.e., pomegranate/sherbet of the highest paradise's garden):  \n\"You ask what sweetness bitter teardrops show, is love?  \nThe juice of Eden's pomegranate in its flow, is love.\"[^4]\n\n[^1]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, ch. 56 (\"hungaama garm hasti-e-na-paaidaar ka\"), [translation](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/56-hungaama-garm-hasti-e-na-paaidaar-ka/translation/).\n[^2]: *Ibid.*, [closing couplet](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/56-hungaama-garm-hasti-e-na-paaidaar-ka/translation/#p-fe6bf4).\n[^3]: *Ibid.*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/56-hungaama-garm-hasti-e-na-paaidaar-ka/translation/#p-f77039).\n[^4]: *Ibid.*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/56-hungaama-garm-hasti-e-na-paaidaar-ka/translation/#p-a4f044).",
